Events.html: 1504 – Christopher Columbus uses his knowledge of a lunar eclipse that night to convince Native Americans to provide him with supplies.
Events.text: Christopher Columbus uses his knowledge of a lunar eclipse that night to convince Native Americans to provide him with supplies.

Events.html: 1644 – Abel Tasman's second Pacific voyage began.

Events.html: 1704 – Queen Anne's War: French forces and Native Americans stage a raid on Deerfield, Massachusetts, killing 56 villagers and taking more than 100 captive.
Events.text: Queen Anne's War: French forces and Native Americans stage a raid on Deerfield, Massachusetts, killing 56 villagers and taking more than 100 captive.

Events.html: 1712 – February 29 is followed by February 30 in Sweden, in a move to abolish the Swedish calendar for a return to the Old style.
Events.text: February 29 is followed by February 30 in Sweden, in a move to abolish the Swedish calendar for a return to the Old style.

Events.html: 1720 – Queen Ulrika Eleonora of Sweden abdicates in favour of her husband, who becomes King Frederick I on 24 March.
Events.text: Queen Ulrika Eleonora of Sweden abdicates in favour of her husband, who becomes King Frederick I on 24 March.

Events.html: 1752 – King Alaungpaya founds Konbaung Dynasty, the last dynasty of Burmese monarchy.
Events.text: King Alaungpaya founds Konbaung Dynasty, the last dynasty of Burmese monarchy.

Events.html: 1768 – Polish nobles formed Bar Confederation.

Events.html: 1796 – The Jay Treaty between the United States and Great Britain comes into force, facilitating ten years of peaceful trade between the two nations.

Events.html: 1864 – American Civil War: Kilpatrick-Dahlgren Raid fails – plans to free 15,000 Union soldiers being held near Richmond, Virginia are thwarted.

Events.html: 1892 – St. Petersburg, Florida is incorporated.

Events.html: 1916 – Child labor: In South Carolina, the minimum working age for factory, mill, and mine workers is raised from twelve to fourteen years old.

Events.html: 1940 – For her role as Mammy in Gone with the Wind, Hattie McDaniel becomes the first African American to win an Academy Award.

Events.html: 1960 – An earthquake in Morocco kills over 3,000 people and nearly destroys Agadir in the southern part of the country.

Events.html: 1964 – In Sydney, Australian swimmer Dawn Fraser sets a new world record in the 100-meter freestyle swimming competition (58.9 seconds).

Events.html: 1972 – Vietnam War: Vietnamization – South Korea withdraws 11,000 of its 48,000 troops from Vietnam.
